{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"36f8a0f2-5f2b-4131-bec6-6c841b7eddff","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. Set properties consistently via `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root or test projects root)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n> If non-test projects share this file, condition on an MSTest import or place it in a common test directory.\n\n## 2. Add the TRX package to each test `.csproj`\n\nThe old VSTest `--logger trx` flag won't work under MTP. Add:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n```\n\n(Use the version compatible with your MSTest 3.8.0 SDK — check NuGet for the latest 1.x.)\n\n## 3. Update the CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test --report-trx\n```\n\n## What each property does\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Activates the MTP runner built into MSTest 3.x |\n| `OutputType Exe` | Required — test projects become self-contained executables |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Makes `dotnet test` delegate to MTP instead of VSTest |\n\nNo other NuGet changes are needed — MSTest 3.8.0 already bundles the runner.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"26dc17d1-8332-4923-905b-c1e08b49d3d1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Enable MTP by setting `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in each project or a shared `Directory.Build.props`.\n2. **For MSTest 3.8.0**: They need the `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` property and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`.\n\n\n3. **CI command**: The `dotnet test --logger trx` command should work, though there may be some edge cases to watch for. With MSTest 3.x, the runner is built-in and gets activated by setting `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` along with `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, while `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` ensures `dotnet test` integrates properly with the new platform.\n\nFor TRX output specifically, they'll likely need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package, though MSTest 3.8 might have built-in TRX support that could eliminate this dependency. Adding the TRX report package to each test project and using `--report-trx` in CI commands instead of the older `--logger trx` syntax. I'll recommend putting the shared properties in a `Directory.Build.props` file at the solution root to keep configuration consistent across all test projects.","outputTokens":1468,"requestId":"0C0C:3E9F58:1EAA6B:2409E3:69F0049A"},"id":"a57c76ca-014c-421b-992b-141cd92f05cb","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:52:05.050Z","parentId":"8841f8b7-fda7-4706-a713-458fc66459af"}
